{"title":"Robust Training of Neural Networks using Scale Invariant Architectures","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Training transformers (e.g., BERT) with non-adaptive SGD is unstable and highly sensitive to parameter/loss scaling due to k-homogeneous structures; practitioners resort to adaptive optimizers (e.g., ADAM) at significant memory cost.","method":"Make the network architecture scale invariant (0-homogeneous) so outputs are insensitive to parameter scale, and train it with vanilla SGD plus weight decay. Concretely, design Scale Invariant BERT (SIBERT): use a (2;2)-homogeneous PreNorm residual block and introduce Scale Invariant Attention by replacing softmax with ReLU followed by row-wise normalization, yielding an attention score that is homogeneous and scale invariant (ATTN: (x,x,x; x+2)). Empirically, SIBERT trained with plain SGD+WD achieves pretraining and downstream performance comparable to BERT trained with ADAM, demonstrating stable optimization without adaptive moments (first effective vanilla-SGD training of a BERT-like model)."},{"problem":"Standard gradient clipping needs hand-tuned, problem-dependent thresholds and can harm performance; for scale-invariant training with SGD+WD, we need clipping that avoids loss spikes yet remains invariant to rescalings of loss, initialization, and reparameterization.","method":"Propose Relative Global Clipping: clip the global gradient norm at √(2 C λ η) · ||x|| (default √C=2). This threshold is invariant to the rescalings (L,η,λ)→(cL,η/c,cλ) and (x,η,λ)→(c x, c^2η, λ/c^2), matching the invariances of SGD+WD, and is derived from the norm equilibrium of scale-invariant dynamics. Theoretically (Theorem 4.8), it improves parameter-norm convergence without requiring bounded gradient norms; empirically it reduces norm spikes and remains infrequent (≈1.5% clipping in SIBERT)."},{"problem":"Even with scale invariance, SGD can be sensitive to initialization and loss scaling, causing slow progress or instability; we need guarantees that non-adaptive methods can converge robustly without tuning to scales.","method":"Analyze GD/SGD with weight decay on scale-invariant losses and prove robust convergence to approximate first-order stationary points. Show the parameter norm converges to Θ((ηλ)^(1/4)) in ˜O(1/(ηλ)) steps with only logarithmic dependence on initialization/loss scale; after norm stabilization, GD achieves O(1/√T) and SGD achieves ˜O(1/T^(1/4)) convergence rates, and the behavior is robust to loss rescaling, initialization rescaling, and reparameterization (A1–A3), up to |log c|/(ηλ) additional steps."}]}
